            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Simply describing `range` as \"end-exclusive\" is insufficient, as it is ambiguous regarding how `end_pos` should be used to represent an entire line. Consider a buffer like this:\r\n```\r\n0123456\r\nabcdefg\r\n```\r\nIf we want to describe the first line, there are two ways to do so\r\n1. `{ start_row = 0, start_col = 0, end_row = 0, end_col = 7 }`\r\n2. `{ start_row = 0, start_col = 0, end_row = 1, end_col = 0 }`\r\n\r\nBoth of the above methods satisfy the \"end-exclusive\" definition. Regarding `extmark`, its documentation states:\r\n> • end_row : ending line of the mark, 0-based inclusive.\r\n• end_col : ending col of the mark, 0-based exclusive, or -1 to extend the range to end of line.\r\n\r\nIIUC, it likely does not support the second usage mentioned above, which is why it throws an out-of-bounds index error when exceeding the buffer. However, LSP does support the second usage, so for our `vim.range`, I believe it would be best to support both usages simultaneously.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-26T12:26:50Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39416#issuecomment-4322020557",
            "id": 4322020557,
            "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/39416",
            "node_id": "IC_kwDOAPphoM8AAAABAZzMzQ",
            "performed_via_github_app": null,
            "reactions": {
                "+1": 0,
                "-1": 0,
                "confused": 0,
