        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": ">  but I handled the pos that is exactly one position beyond the buffer because our range is described as \"end-exclusive.\" Therefore, such an end_pos combined with a start_pos can represent a range to the end of the buffer, which should be seen as valid and does not throw errors.\r\n\r\nI handled that case because it would cause errors otherwise.\r\n\r\nIt's been a while since I wrote that code and I had forgot about how it was supposed to work. Today, seeing it with fresh eyes, I realized that I made some wrong assumptions in this PR. I'll close it, but it may be worth adding a comment to explain why the conversion is only done in that particular case and only in one direction.\r\n\r\nMy understanding was that `vim.Range`'s internal representation is meant to follow tree-sitter's one as per https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/36397#discussion_r2480108401 . Both tree-sitter and extmark indexing represent a range that ends in a newline with an end position that is row-exclusive and col-0. So, it seems like there would be no need to make any conversion between both representations. But, APIs that use extmark indexing throw an out-of-bound error when trying to use that kind of range in the last line of a file.\r\n\r\nOn the buffer\r\n\r\n```\r\nSome text\r\nSome other text\r\n```\r\n\r\n`vim.api.nvim_buf_get_text(0, 0, 0, 1, 0, {})` returns `{\"Some text\", \"\"}`. The range includes the trailing newline.\r\n\r\nOn the buffer\r\n\r\n```\r\nSome text\r\n```\r\n\r\n`vim.api.nvim_buf_get_text(0, 0, 0, 1, 0, {})` throws an index-out-of-bounds error, probably because the internal representation of the buffer doesn't include a trailing newline.\r\n\r\nThat's why on my original implementation would convert the `vim.Range` `{0, 0, 1, 0}` into the extmark range `{0, 0, 0, 9}` for the second buffer, to avoid an error. But, this conversion losses information. Ranges that include and that do not include a trailing newline end up using the same representation. That's why the conversion wasn't being made on the opposite direction, because not all extmark ranges in the form `{0, 0, 0, 9}` would have need to be converted to `vim.Range` ranges in the form `{0, 0, 1, 0}`.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-26T16:43:58Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39416#issuecomment-4322507363",
            "id": 4322507363,
            "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/39416",
            "node_id": "IC_kwDOAPphoM8AAAABAaQ6Yw",
            "performed_via_github_app": null,
